/** \page data Data representations

\section data_s11 S-parameters

S-parameters, or scattering parameters, are a way of representing
the response of a network to stimuli at its ports. The S-parameters
are named \f$S_{ij}\f$, where \f$i\f$ is the port at which the response is measured, 
and \f$j\f$ is the port at which the stimulus is applied. Typically,
S-parameters are represented as complex numbers, with the real part representing
the in-phase response and the imaginary part representing the quadrature.

In a nanoVNA,
which has two ports, the stimulus is applied to port 1, and the 
response is measured at both. So we have the following S-parameters:
- <B>\f$S_{11}\f$</B>: The response at port 1 when the stimulus is applied 
to port 1. This is also known as the reflection coefficient.
- <B>\f$S_{21}\f$</B>: The response at port 2 when the stimulus is applied to port 1. 
This is also known as the forward transmission coefficient.

\section data_nanovna S-parameters from the nanoVNA

The format of the request and response to the nanoVNA is defined
by the nanoVNA's firmware. Currently, the application only
supports the nanoVNA-H, but other models may be supported in the future.

ZZAVNAD sends a request to the nanoVNA to perform a scan, which includes
the start frequency, stop frequency and number of samples. It
also states whether just \f$S_{11}\f$ is required or both \f$S_{11}\f$ and \f$S_{21}\f$. 
The nanoVNA responds with the frequency and the real and imaginary parts
of the S-parameters at that frequency.

