\section data_transforms Transformations of S-parameters

As is shown in \ref displays, the S-parameters can be transformed
into a number of different representations.

\subsection data_transforms_swr SWR

The \f$S_{11}\f$ parameter can be converted to SWR using the following formula:
\f[
SWR = \frac{1 + |S_{11}|}{1 - |S_{11}|} 
\f]

where \f$|S_{11}|\f$ is the magnitude of the \f$S_{11}\f$ parameter.

\subsection data_transforms_impedace Impedance

The \f$S_{11}\f$ parameter can be converted to a complex impedance using the following formula:
\f[
Z = Z_0 \cdot \frac{1 + S_{11}}{1 - S_{11}}
\f]

where \f$Z_0\f$ is the characteristic impedance of the system, which is typically 50&nbsp;&Omega;.

The complex impedance \f$Z\f$ can be represented as a complex number,
as a pair of real numbers representing the resistance and reactance or as
a pair of real numbers representing the magnitude and angle. The relationships 
between these representations are as follows:
\f[
Z = R + jX = |Z| e^{j\theta}
\f]
\f[
R = |Z| \cos(\theta)
\f]
\f[
X = |Z| \sin(\theta)
\f]
where \f$R\f$ is the resistance, \f$X\f$ is the reactance, \f$|Z|\f$ is the magnitude
of the impedance and \f$\theta\f$ is the angle of the impedance.

In the equation above, \f$\theta\f$ is the angle in radians, however
in the application, the angle is typically displayed in degrees.

*/

